Memory map

Purpose:
- Configuration-specific memory map for active `.uai`, local durable docs, MATM routes, and companion documentation.

Verification status: active operational memory; verify with `.uai/long-term-memory.uai`, `.uai/long-term-pointer-ledger.uai`, and route evidence before relying on it.
Memory scope: memory layers, routing, durable targets, and truth boundaries.
Public-safe status: safe for source control; contains route names and paths only, no credentials.
Update route: update this map when memory layers, durable targets, setup modes, or route boundaries change.
Source of truth: `.uai/totem.uai`, `.uai/long-term-memory.uai`, `.uai/long-term-pointer-ledger.uai`, and MemoryEndpoints.com route contracts.
Next action for agents: choose the correct memory layer before writing or retrieving project facts.
Must not expose: raw API keys, bearer tokens, FTP credentials, database passwords, private keys, private handoff payloads, raw one-time keys, raw private memory bodies, or private workspace identifiers.

Memory layers:
- Active startup memory: `.uai/` files in the startup-packet read order.
- Human/agent front door: `AGENTS.md`, `workspace.uai`, and `.uai/readme.human`.
- Active dropped-file intake: `agent-file-handoff/Content` and `agent-file-handoff/Improvement`.
- Transitional local migration and verification evidence: `docs/long-term-memory/` and `docs/reports/`; move knowledge deliberately into hosted MATM and remove the parallel `docs/` hierarchy after migration is complete.
- Hosted durable MATM: MemoryEndpoints.com protected routes when authenticated.
- Database-backed knowledge wiki: protected `matm_crawl_sources` and `matm_search_documents` rows exposed through `/knowledge`, `/api/matm/knowledge-tree`, and `/api/matm/knowledge-documents`.
- Curated external web index: protected `matm_external_links` and `matm_external_link_mentions` rows exposed through `/api/matm/internet-search` and `/api/matm/external-links`, with the same citations visible on authenticated wiki pages.
- Public companion docs: MultiAgentMemory.com source under `sites/multiagentmemory.com/`.

Rules:
- Durable memory augments active `.uai`; it never retires local `.uai`.
- `.uai` contains pointers and current operating state, not raw secrets or long report bodies.
- README.md files are human documentation, not memory-package state.
- Research/report intake is processed one file at a time. Preserve one canonical source page, split multi-topic material into reviewed semantic knowledge pages, and create compact MATM summaries that link back to those pages. Do not bulk-import archives or process multiple source files as one intake operation.
- Review each compact MATM summary as one memory decision with protected readback. Promotion preserves current, proposed, historical, risk, decision, evidence, and other typed meaning; it is not an authority upgrade.
- Use a reviewer-authored overlay for corrected current guidance when raw research mixes valid principles with stale or unsafe claims. Preserve exact whole-source and selected-source hashes, retain the raw source as protected historical evidence, and never store the local overlay path in hosted metadata.
- Every wiki knowledge document needs a title, description, keywords, and one or more taxonomy paths. Exact search is not enough; agents must be able to browse contextual hierarchy paths such as `AI infrastructure > tokenization > prompt optimization`. One canonical document can appear in multiple hierarchies without duplicating the stored body.
- Every retained external citation needs a canonical URL record with site name, page title, description, keywords, host, review state, and crawl state. A separate mention record preserves why a knowledge page cites it, including relationship, anchor text, context, label, and order.
- Historical availability findings and current observations are separate knowledge claims. Preserve the original source and access metadata for audit, but require a fresh request and explicit failure classification before recalling an endpoint as currently unavailable or WAF-blocked.
- Link current primary standards beside historical or proposed claims when their interpretation matters. Agents should be able to crawl from a raw proposal to the governing robots, sitemap, HTTP, CORS, OpenAPI, MCP, A2A, or well-known-URI source without relying on exact phrase search.
- Keep interoperability layers independently attributable in memory. UAI-1 records portable exchange evidence, Project Handoff and local `.uai` preserve repository context, MCP connects hosts to tools and resources, implemented peer protocols coordinate agents, schemas validate structure, and service authorization controls access.
- Store capability, identity, signing, and product-integration claims with explicit authority and lifecycle. A declaration or signature is not authorization or truth, an unrelated homonym is not product evidence, and a proposed adapter remains proposed until implemented and verified.
- Keep execution telemetry out of startup memory and public exchange by default. Promote only reviewed, bounded, redacted outcomes and protected evidence pointers; raw stdout, stderr, arguments, environment data, credentials, hidden prompts, private traces, exploit recipes, and complete snapshots do not belong in `.uai`, public UAI, public profiles, or public ledgers.
- Preserve execution-control distinctions in memory: the runtime owns work, authorization, credentials, limits, cleanup, and recovery; UAI carries reviewed evidence; MCP connects hosts to tools and resources; schemas validate structure; sandbox backends reduce selected exposure. None silently inherits another layer's authority.
- Shared memory needs explicit ownership, provenance, authority, retention, and concurrency semantics. Prefer read-only policy context and append-safe evidence; use compare-before-replace or another version check for mutable state, and treat full shared-block rewrites as destructive last-write-wins behavior unless the implementation proves stronger conflict handling.
- Multi-agent meeting transcripts and model outputs are coordination evidence, not automatic durable truth. Promote only compact source-linked claims through individual review, keep current, historical, proposed, risk, and decision meanings intact, and preserve an accountable human escalation path.
- The home page and public discovery files are orientation only. Wiki trees, deep routes, search results, external-link records, and hosted memory remain credential-bound company/workspace/project data; users and accounts never become knowledge ownership scopes.
- Keep human and agent access on the same protected knowledge graph. Human-readable linked wiki pages and machine-readable APIs may differ in representation but must preserve the same tenant, lifecycle, authority, provenance, taxonomy, citation, and authorization meaning.
- Preserve an existing explicit canonical external-link review disposition when adding an unreviewed citation. Canonicalize crawl policy before fingerprint and readback, and record requested versus effective status in redacted evidence.
- Discovery and metadata do not create authority: robots controls crawling, `llms.txt` can orient public consumers, manifests and hashes can carry bounded integrity evidence, OpenAPI describes HTTP, MCP connects tools and context, and the service still authenticates and authorizes every protected operation.
